                        Buy or subscribe

To understand the Arctic overturning circulation, Marius Årthun of the University of Bergen, and Bjerknes Centre for Climate Research, Norway, and colleagues used high-resolution ocean reanalysis data to compare recent decades. They show that the growing intrusion of warm Atlantic waters into the Arctic is driving sea-ice loss and shifting dense water formation from the Nordic Seas poleward into the northern Barents Sea and the Nansen Basin. This strengthens the Arctic Ocean overturning circulation, and dense water export has remained stable, thus contributing to maintaining the lower limb of the AMOC.Original reference: Sci. Adv. 11, eadu1794 (2025)



